I feel your pain. Security is great until it starts feeling like a part-time job. Since you're on Arch and using Ed25519 (excellent choice, by the way—it's fast and secure), the solution is to use an SSH Agent.

This allows you to type your passphrase once per session, and the agent handles the "handshakes" for you in the background.

1. The Quick Fix: ssh-agent
If you just want peace and quiet for your current terminal session, run these commands:

Bash
eval $(ssh-agent -s)
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
You’ll enter your passphrase once, and you're set until you close that terminal.

2. The Permanent Fix (The "Arch Way")
Since you’re on Arch, you likely want this to "just work" when you log in. The most robust way to do this is via systemd user services or your .bash_profile.

However, the most user-friendly method for most Arch users is adding a snippet to your ~/.ssh/config file to work with a manager like Keychain or the built-in desktop keyring.

Option A: Using keychain (Recommended)
Keychain is a tidy manager that ensures only one agent runs and survives terminal restarts.

Install it: sudo pacman -S keychain

Add to your shell config (e.g., ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc):

Bash
/usr/bin/keychain --quiet --agents ssh id_ed25519
source $HOME/.keychain/$HOSTNAME-sh
Option B: If you use a Desktop Environment (GNOME/KDE)
If you are using GNOME or KDE, they usually have a built-in "Secret Service" (like gnome-keyring).

Open your ~/.ssh/config (create it if it doesn't exist).

Add these lines:

Plaintext
Host *
  AddKeysToAgent yes
This tells SSH to automatically "remember" any key you use by pushing it into whatever agent is running.

3. Comparison of Methods
Method	Effort	Persistence	Best For...
Manual ssh-add	Low	Session only	One-off tasks
Keychain	Medium	Persistent	Minimalist setups/Window Managers (i3, sway)
Desktop Keyring	Low	Persistent	Full Desktop Environments (GNOME, KDE, XFCE)
