That snippet is almost perfect, but there is one small technicality with how eval and keychain interact that might cause it to prompt you for a password every single time you open a new terminal tab—which defeats the purpose!

1. Refined .bashrc Logic
When you use --eval, keychain outputs the shell variables needed to find the running agent. To make sure it only asks for your password once per boot (rather than once per terminal window), use this slightly adjusted version:

Bash
# Check if keychain is installed
if command -v keychain >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    # --inherit-any tells keychain to look for existing agents before starting a new one
    eval $(keychain --eval --quiet --agents ssh --inherit-any id_ed25519)
fi
Why the change? The --inherit-any flag ensures that if you already unlocked your key in one terminal, the second terminal you open will "hook into" that same session instead of asking again.

2. The Hyprland Way
In a Wayland compositor like Hyprland, the environment variables (like SSH_AUTH_SOCK) often need to be "exported" so that GUI apps (like VS Code or a Git GUI) can see the agent too.

Step A: Auto-start with Hyprland
Instead of relying purely on the terminal opening to start the agent, you can tell Hyprland to kick things off the moment you log in. Add this to your hyprland.conf:

Plaintext
# Start keychain for your ed25519 key on login
exec-once = keychain --agents ssh id_ed25519
Step B: Sharing variables with Wayland
To ensure that any process started by Hyprland knows where the SSH agent is, you should update the user environment. In your .bashrc (right after the keychain eval line), add:

Bash
# Share the SSH agent with the rest of the Hyprland session
if [ -n "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ]; then
    dbus-update-activation-environment --systemd SSH_AUTH_SOCK
fi
3. Pro-Tip: The "Lazy" SSH Config
Since you're using Hyprland, you're likely a fan of efficiency. You can make SSH even smarter by editing ~/.ssh/config:

Plaintext
Host *
    AddKeysToAgent yes
    IgnoreUnknown UseKeychain
    UseKeychain yes      # Specific to Apple, but safe to keep for cross-platform
What this does: The moment you run ssh your-server, SSH will look for your key, see it's not in the agent, prompt you for the password once, and then automatically "stuff" it into the keychain agent for you. You won't even need to run ssh-add manually.

Summary Checklist
Install: sudo pacman -S keychain

Hyprland Config: Add exec-once = keychain --agents ssh id_ed25519

Bashrc: Use the eval block with --inherit-any.

Reboot/Relog: Enjoy the silence of never typing that passphrase again today.

